## Thread.Abort Migration → .NET 8

### Pattern Analysis

Your code has **four** patterns that need migration:

| Location | Pattern | Issue in .NET 8 |
|---|---|---|
| `Stop()` → `_workerThread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Exception as control flow | Never thrown in .NET 8 |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `GetNextItem()` "may block" | Blocking call interruption | Abort can't interrupt it anymore |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop (replaces ResetAbort + loop-condition check)
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

### Key Changes Explained

1. **`Thread.Abort()` → `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()`** — signals the token; the loop checks `token.IsCancellationRequested` cooperatively.

2. **`catch (ThreadAbortException)` → `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (…)`** — the `when` guard ensures you only catch *your* cancellation, not an unrelated one. Cleanup logic (`RollbackCurrentTransaction`) is preserved.

3. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` → `break`** — ResetAbort kept the thread alive so `finally` could run. With cooperative cancellation, `finally` always runs normally. Use `break` to exit the loop after cleanup.

4. **`Thread.Sleep(2000)` → `Thread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2))`** — actually waits for the thread to finish instead of blindly sleeping.

5. **`GetNextItem()` must accept the token** — this is critical. If it blocks on I/O or a queue, it needs the token to wake up:

```csharp
// If using BlockingCollection<T>:
var item = _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException on cancel

// If using a custom blocking wait:
var item = GetNextItem(token);
// Inside: use token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(timeout) instead of Thread.Sleep
```

### ⚠️ Pitfalls to Watch

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| **`GetNextItem()` ignores the token** | Cancellation stalls until the blocking call returns on its own. Pass and check the token in every blocking method. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks timers and callbacks. Always `Dispose()` it. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Without the `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` guard, you'll swallow cancellations from inner operations. |
| **Expecting instant cancellation** | Cooperative cancellation only works at checkpoints. If `ProcessItem()` is long-running, add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside it at regular intervals. |
